Even with physical disabilities, I struggle with imposter syndrome. ⁣
⁣
It all feels like a foreign language in my mouth. Speaking words, I don’t understand. ⁣
Terrified of offending everyone, 𝘪𝘯𝘤𝘭𝘶𝘥𝘪𝘯𝘨 𝘮𝘺𝘴𝘦𝘭𝘧.⁣
⁣
I have spent nearly a year fighting internalized ableism, bubbling up to the surface like boiling water. ♨️⁣
⁣
Moving through a world that constantly emphasizes that I am unwelcome within the parameters of normalcy.⁣
⁣
𝗕𝘂𝘁 𝘀𝘁𝗶𝗹𝗹, 𝗜 𝘁𝗿𝘆. ⛅️⁣
⁣
• I strive for a higher education.⁣
• I plan my wedding.⁣
• I apply for disability over and over and over.⁣
⁣
Today, I’m thinking of the words of Mary Oliver.⁣
⁣
“I don’t want to end up, simply having visited this world.”⁣
⁣
So on this day of all the days, I live my damn life —and I’m proud of me for that. 🖤⁣
⁣
⁣
Happy international day of disability to the many powerful people out there. ⁣
⁣
Wow, I love you. ⁣
⁣
⁣

This is how I remember him best.⁣
⁣
— Driving with the top down, being silly.⁣
⁣
— Wind in our hair, music blasting.⁣
⁣
My dad has always meant the world to me.⁣
⁣
It took me a long time to realize how alike we are.⁣
⁣
I’m so thankful that I can permanently hear his voice in my head, telling me jokes. 🥹⁣
⁣
Happy birthday, Paps. ⁣
⁣
You should be 65 years old today. ⁣
Telling us the same crazy stories on a loop. ⁣
Blasting Bruno Mars.⁣
⁣
⁣
In honor of you, I’ll be having a beer and some really epic food with the love of my life. Can you believe we’re getting married finally? 🫠⁣
⁣
I love you forever. Missing you has become a full-time job.⁣
⁣
Happy birthday, Pop. Wish you were here. ♥️⁣
⁣
⁣
⁣

🗓️ December 28th: the day I died and came back someone different. ⁣
⁣
I went to sleep for surgery, knowing we needed to aggressively go after my spinal cord tumor in order to save my life. ⁣
⁣
I woke up alone, past visiting hours… unable to use my hands, unable to move my leg. ⁣
⁣
In a matter of several unconscious hours, everything about my life changed. 💀⁣
⁣
When you die, everything around you does too, and that plagues you with a constant ache.⁣
⁣
⁣
Most days, I beg the universe to give me back the life I had… which is one of the biggest tragedies of all — my stubborn refusal to fully let go. ⁣
⁣
I will never be who I was on December 27, 2021 again. I’ll never dance with full abandon or hike volcanoes. 🕯️⁣
⁣
I’ll always be twice as terrified of danger, because I don’t have the ability to just run and hide…⁣
⁣
Eventually, I hope I can let the grief and the joy coexist easily on this day. ⁣
⁣
But right now, the agony is colossal. ⁣
The loss is blinding. ⁣
I know the light is there, but I’m not ready to look. ⁣
⁣
Rest in peace, sweet heart of mine. ⁣
⁣
Today, you are not alone. 🖤⁣
⁣
⁣
⁣

2022, thank you. 🖤⁣
⁣
Even through the bad, the very hard, the hurting… Thank you. ⁣
⁣
You gave me the opportunity to find my way back to life. ⁣
⁣
And the things I was able to do?⁣
💌 straight As for my first semester of grad school.⁣
💌 get engaged to the love of my life.⁣
💌 relearn to fucking walk.⁣
⁣
This year was no joke. 🌪️⁣
⁣
And even through *alllll* the tears, I worked for it. ⁣
⁣
AAAND: I’m ready to wake up tomorrow & keep going. ⁣
⁣
⁣
Cheers, my loves. ⁣
⁣
⁣

I believe that we mourn past versions of ourselves in the same way we grieve the loss of loved ones.⁣ ☝🏻
⁣
It’s what I’m dedicating my grad school research to.⁣
⁣
The idea of 𝗶𝗱𝗲𝗻𝘁𝗶𝘁𝘆 𝗱𝗶𝘀𝗿𝘂𝗽𝘁𝗶𝗼𝗻. 💀⁣
⁣
// Not knowing who you are or how you relate to the world after a trauma.⁣
⁣
⁣
I’ve been living in that place for more than a year, now. ⁣
⁣
But, as if I’m 𝘧𝘪𝘯𝘢𝘭𝘭𝘺 breathing again, I feel like I am settling into my new skin.⁣
⁣
I just want to be who I am right now. 🖤⁣
⁣
⁣

TW: body image. I spend an annoying amount of time thinking about my body. ⁣⚖️
⁣
~ how it curves⁣
~ when it bloats⁣
~ where it wrinkles⁣
⁣
I gained 20 pounds in the span of a month bc of the steroids that were managing my pain. ⁣
⁣
Trying to improve my quality of life meant compromising on my waistline, and I hate how often that bugs me.⁣
⁣
⁣
Doubting my body stole my joy. ⁣❤️‍🩹
⁣
⁣I stopped basking because I suddenly felt so judged. ⁣
⁣
I’d find pockets of peace in celebrity bodies that looked like mine, just to discover they were being fat shamed. ⁣
⁣
⁣
I guess all of this is a reminder that other people’s bodies are not your fucking business. ⁣⚡️
⁣
Let people like themselves. ⁣
𝘐 𝘳𝘦𝘱𝘦𝘢𝘵: let people like themselves. ⁣
⁣
In every body that houses their heart. 🖤

My life looks nothing like I thought it would at 29. 
⁣
I have wrinkles and scars and rosacea. ⁣
⁣
Most days, I’m just working to keep my head up — literally. 💤⁣
⁣
But how cool is it that I get a chance to do that?⁣
⁣
How incredibly lucky am I to have made it this far?⁣
⁣
𝗜 𝗵𝗮𝘃𝗲 𝗹𝗶𝘃𝗲𝗱 𝗹𝗼𝗻𝗴 𝗲𝗻𝗼𝘂𝗴𝗵 𝘁𝗼 𝗿𝗲𝗶𝗻𝘃𝗲𝗻𝘁 𝗺𝘆𝘀𝗲𝗹𝗳.⁣
⁣
To gather up my ashes and try again.⁣
⁣
I never want to look back and regret not having cherished the sweetness of time. ⁣
⁣
So this is me: on my way out the door of another decade. 🖤 Soft / warm / alive. ⁣
⁣
⁣
⁣

JUST BETWEEN US // Sara and Sumaya 

JUST BETWEEN US is an ever-evolving observation and documentation of queer love and intimacy. The ways in which we hold each other — literally and figuratively. The ways in which we revere each other. And protect each other. And honor each other. The ways in which we find hope in each other. And, importantly, the ways in which we find home in each other. 

As I’ve said before, I am of the belief that photographs are love letters. That they can encapsulate love in a way that words often cannot. JUST BETWEEN US is my love letter to queer love. My love letter to my community. 

Thank you for being here.

xx,
Sam

I want my platform to feel more like who I am now.

Not only am I two years deep in my recovery from a spinal cord tumor, I am halfway through my grad school program in humanistic and existential psychology.

I spend 99.9% of my time reflecting on how trauma impacts our identity.

How do we effectively grieve and move on when we’ve never been given the tools to do so?

What I’m saying is: I wanna talk to you more.

I hope you’ll listen. 🖤

What drives us as human beings? 💭

Through my research on death & transformation, I ran into the idea of Terror Management Theory.

This idea that our fear of death subconsciously motivates everything we do over the course of our lives.

But lately, I’ve been thinking there might be more to it than that…

What do you think? 💡

My mom has literally saved my life. 🤕

When I woke up paralyzed, she fought her way to my hospital bedside and slept in the chair beside me.

She held my hand as I wept at 4:30am. 

She went to every single doctor’s appointment.

She bathed me, cooked for me, and picked me up off the floor when I fell.

I don’t know how I could have made it through any of this without her.

My mom is truly my best friend. 💘

And tonight, I get to hug her.

Happy Mother’s Day, Susie, Q. 💕🌷

#mothersday2023 #momsrock #momsruntheworld #mymomismyhero #mymama #meandmymom

This time of year is especially hard for me. 😔

In 2019, these were my last weeks with my dad before he suddenly died in June.

My antidepressants have made it easier to block out some of the intense grief, but late May will always break my heart. 💌

Friends: it’s mental health awareness month — and I refuse to keep this part of me a secret. 🕯️

The sadness is powerful, but so am I. 

We can face our worst pain. Together. 🖤

#mentalhealthmonth #griefandloss #griefawareness #antidepressants #mentalhealthawarenessmonth #cryingmyeyesout

When your body is dying, your priorities change. 🫀

Your friendships, your career goals, the way you think about time…

I’ve been alive for 30 years. Three full decades. 🫶🏻

My 20s were nothing like I thought they’d be.

• I coped with sexual assault. 
• with the death of my dad. 
• with getting sick & becoming disabled. 

And what I learned? ⬇️

— Life is not about what you achieve; what benchmarks you hit. 

1️⃣ I didn’t get married… but I found the love of my life. Someone who taught me what a healthy relationship feels like.

2️⃣ I didn’t become a millionaire… but I figured out my purpose. The understanding of Self that is leading me to my career.

3️⃣ I didn’t land a role on Broadway… but I met my best friends while pursuing it. Friendships that have given me more warmth than I’ve ever received. 

My 20s have been complicated and, at times, deeply painful.

They’ve also been vibrant and riiiiich in experience. 🌙

And I survived ALLLL of it — even the things I wasn’t sure I would.

So happy birthday to every version of my sweet heart; to everyone I have been, and to everyone I will become. 

But most importantly: to who I am right this very second. At 30 years old. 💖 MUAH

#30thbirthdaycelebration #turning30 #ilived #30yearsold #strongwomenrule #goodbye20s #outwiththeoldinwiththenew #ontothenextchapter

The other night, I had a giant panic attack.

I can’t name one thing about my life that I recognize.

It scares me to remember that my body is permanently different.

That I can try all I want, but some nerve damage is just nerve damage.

But the fragility of life is part of what makes it beautiful. 

This is me trying, trying, trying. Even when it hurts like hell.

🖤

#disabledlivesmatter #youarestrongenough #disabilityadvocate #disabledandproud #traumasurvivors #everythingwillbeokay

☝🏼1 in 4 American adults have some type of disability (hi, that’s a LOT of people!)

While I’m truly just starting to scratch the surface on what I know about disability and what I used to believe, it’s a unique perspective when it affects someone you deeply love on a daily basis.

It’s makes me so uncomfortable when people imply that there is some sort of hierarchy in our relationship… that I’m a “hero” or a “saint” of some kind.

Because first of all, have you SEEN my fiancée?? She’s hot AF 🔥🔥🔥

And second, because there are so many different types of labor and responsibility in a relationship. Just because I can carry a suitcase up a flight of stairs doesn’t mean I’m somehow “doing more.” 

I mean, she’s the one who unpacks the damn thing 😅

Just like any relationship, you can’t see everything about it from the outside. And we’re truly happy together — what we do works for us ✌️💕

What kind of things are you curious to learn about disability? ⬇️⬇️⬇️

#interabledcouple #loveislove #lesbiancouplegoals #pridemonth2023 #disabilityadvocate

We moved to Manhattan in February 2019. 🏙️

Madly in love and wiiiild with dreams.

We had date nights w. our friends!! 
Memorized a jungle!!
Hid from a pandemic!!

We realized the strength of our relationship, through being tested again, again, and again.🩺💊💉

And not once did we resent the chaotic beauty of this place.

But it felt like time for a fresh start. 🌒

So on May 15, we blew our kisses and said goodbye to New York City.

Maybe for a bit, maybe for forever. 
— Nothing is ever permanent, sweet love.

We are just blooming somewhere else for a while. 🌻🌻🌻

#leavingnyc #movingonwithlife #crosscountrymove #freshstarts #sayinggoodbye #goodbyenyc

Losing my handwriting broke my heart. 📖

When they say your hands come back slowly post-paralysis, they freaking mean it. 

There’s so much frustration and sadness woven throughout the day — you can’t do your hair, open a soda, tie your shoes. 

So when the world starts bleeding back in again, you notice it. 💡

This is my handwriting in June 2023, 18 months after I was paralyzed. 🖤

Even with imperfections, I love it profoundly.

Thanks for cheering me on. 🥹

#paralyzed #paralysisrecovery #ontheroadtorecovery #disabilitypride #mybodyismine #disabilitylife

I’ll never get over being surprised by this love. 💖

I grew up thinking I would marry a big, strong man.

Even when I came out, I still thought it was inevitable…

So imagine my surprise when I left my first date with tiny Sumaya, knowing full well I had just gotten ice cream with my future wife. 💍

The way she provides for us, builds our furniture, maps out the logistics of life.

BIG NEWS: I’m restarting my business.

After:
* three years of cancer treatment 
* switching paths for a master’s in psychology 
* one giant move across the country
* and reworking my identity over and over
I’m ready to share what I’ve learned about transformation.

The truth is: trauma leaves a mark.

And often, we get so caught up in the day-to-day that we rarely slow down to acknowledge its impact.

Cue anxiety, burnout, feeling stuck, and overall identity confusion.

I want to guide people through the chaos, helping them reestablish who they are on the other side of change.

Whatever that change may be — sickness, a breakup, a career shift — we are altered. 

There simply is no going back to before.

But the beautiful secret is: once you accept that truth, you get to become who you are.

Transformation is scary. I know firsthand.

Let’s do it together — coming verrrry soon. 🖤

PS I love you and I like you and I’ve missed you so much.

In 2021, I woke up from surgery without the use of my right leg or hands.🦽

For almost 2 years, I have been re-learning how to exist in the world that is built for one type of body — not mine. 

Right now, I’m rewiring my brain to take up the space it deserves. 🧠

I’m learning to advocate for myself, when people make me feel like my needs are inconvenient.

A month and a half ago, my landlord took away our elevator, and gave us absolutely no accommodation support, even though we live on the top floor of our building.

!! This kind of craziness happens all the freaking time.

I refuse to live the rest of my life feeling guilty about this body that has survived so much.

My disability was not a mistake. 👏🏻

It was how I survived. 
It’s the reason I woke up from surgery at all. 🖤🐍

Today marks two years since the day I went into surgery and woke up paralyzed. 🗓️

I came out of anesthesia with the same brain, but a different body.

That level of disconnect is intense on every level.

& I’d be lying if I said it’s all good now. 

That I don’t still have impossibly hard days where I wanna crawl out of my skin or feel sick to my stomach with grief.

But I’ve worked very hard to forgive my body for the things it had to do to survive. 

And while healing has not been a straightforward progression of getting better and better, the fact of the matter is: the days do keep coming.

That detail is never lost on me, and omg I’m thankful for it.

I’ll keep going if you will. 🖤

When I became disabled, I was scared that I would no longer be able to travel the world comfortably.

But I refuse to stop living !!

So instead: I’m going to rate the accessibility of the world. 🌎

First stop: Vatican City in Rome, Italy.

YAYS: 
- kind security guards who wanted to help
- some areas with flat ground

NO WAYS:
- narrow stairwells
- few handrails
- limited opportunities to sit down 
- almost no elevators
- super long distances to walk

Alsoooo… visitors can only see certain areas with a tour, which isn’t always an accessible option. 🤷🏻‍♀️

Seeing the Sistine chapel was breathtaking, but Vatican City was pretty inaccessible across-the-board. I was freaking exhausted.

Final vote: 4/10 stars. 🫠
